These are rock solid little guns and tuck nicely into a waist band, coat pocket or purse.

In addition to lawful owners, many gangsters of the pre-World War II era favored the Model 1903 and Model 1908 because they were relatively small and easily concealed. It is said that Al Capone kept one in his coat pocket and Bonnie Parker used one to break Clyde Barrow out of jail after smuggling it into the jail by taping it to her thigh. Bank robber John Dillinger was carrying this model of pistol when he was shot by FBI agents outside the Biograph theater on July 22, 1934, and another famous bank robber, Willie Sutton kept one when was captured by police in Brooklyn on February 18, 1952.

title: For Sale:  Detonics .45 Mark III Combat Master -- The Original Mini 1911, Detonics Combat Master
postcontent: The Detonics Combat Master has a had a very interesting history.  The Detonics Combat Master was the first really small and compact 1911-pattern pistol to be produced in significant numbers.  Law enforcement fell in love with it immediately due to its diminutive size and quality.  The Detonics started in Seattle Washington in the late 70's and in the early 80's the Mark series introduced the bulged barrel end so that the pistol did not require a bushing.  It also incorporated double and triple recoil springs.  It was the first production 1911-pattern which was throated and ramped for hollow-points.  This gun is in very nice condition.  The Detonics Mark III has hard chrome finish.  This is a rare pistol that is a great size for concealed carry.  It is a bit heavy but this really helps with the recoil.  It comes with 2 original magazines and original Pachmayr grips.  Asking $750 or best reasonable cash offer.  Looking for a nice .22 Magnum Rifle but cash is King on this deal so I can order what I'm looking for.  Call/Text Rick 5O5*6IO*529I

title: For Sale/Trade:  German K98 with Gew98 receiver 1916 Berlin
postcontent: I have a WWI era Gew98 that was converted to a K98 for sale or trade. Excellent condition with some slight pitting on the side of the receiver. Dutsche Waffen-Und Munitionsfabriken Berlin 1916 stamped receiver. From what I've been told, this is a pre-war Gew98 that was reworked in 1938. Nazi Germany took its existing G98s left over and often modernized them to K98 standards. This meant cutting down, or in this case replacing the barrel, changing the stock, bolts, rear sights, etc. It has a BO stamp on the barrel, which should indicate a Brohmler Brothers manufacture. All #s that are on the gun match. The stock looks like a Russian capture, but there is no "x" on the receiver. There is no electro pencil markings. There are imperial Germany proof markings on it, along with Nazi factory code marks. The bore is bright, VG lands with slight frost. I fired 5 rounds to check for function, it works a-ok! It has a cleaning rod, and if I can find it, I have a sight hood to include as well. I'm in and around knoxville quite often, and I'm willing to travel if you are. Also can provide more pictures if you want them.

title: For Sale:  VERY RARE SIG P220ST P220 full stainless, Nitron finish.
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very rare Sig P220ST in Nitron finish. For those unfamiliar with the ST model it is full stainless steel, both frame and slide. SIG produced under 80 of these pistols for testing and evaluation by LE agencies. These were the only P220ST pistols that ever left the SIG factory with the Nitron finish and they received special attention in production. It comes exactly as pictured from the factory with Hogue rubber grips, Trijicon marked night sights that shine bright, and 2 factory 8rd magazines. Light not included.

The entire thread dedicated to these special pieces can be found on Sigforum. I never had a single FTF/FTE, it ran flawlessly with any ammo.

$900. PRICE DROP TO $850. Want to trade specifically for a Sig P228. Preference leans towards older stamped West German models rather than newer ones with milled slides.
